  "prompt": "What software do Ghibli / Japanese studios use to create anime?",
  "response": "Japanese animation studios, including Studio Ghibli, use various software for different stages of anime production:\n\n2D Animation Software:\n1. Toon Boom Harmony\n2. Adobe Animate (formerly Flash)\n3. TVPaint\n4. OpenToonz (open-source, used by Ghibli)\n\nDigital Painting/Backgrounds:\n1. Adobe Photoshop\n2. Clip Studio Paint\n3. RETAS Studio (popular in Japan)\n\n3D Modeling/Animation (when used):\n1. Autodesk Maya\n2. Blender\n3. Autodesk 3ds Max\n\nCompositing and Post-Production:\n1. Adobe After Effects\n2. Nuke\n3. Fusion\n\nStudio Ghibli specifically is known for maintaining a more traditional hand-drawn animation style, often using OpenToonz for digital coloring and compositing. While they've incorporated some digital techniques, they still heavily rely on hand-drawn animation techniques.\n\nOther major studios like Kyoto Animation, A-1 Pictures, and Production I.G. use similar software suites, though the exact workflow varies by studio.",
